{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780373635850,"sessionID":"ses_1797707a9ffehSuq7kNyovejK9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_PGVcCT5YIV3g2D2rQmYictjx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"D4|routine|LS-002|usefulness|approximate|n=2|assets|expectedAssets","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/011-sk-code-routing-efficiency-remediation/research","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 103 matches (showing first 100)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/011-sk-code-routing-efficiency-remediation/research/iterations/iteration-007.md:\n  Line 1: SKILL ROUTING: User specified deep-research agent. I’ll treat this as read-only repository-grounded research and produce the iteration markdown in the response, not mutate files.Memory trigger lookup is unavailable (`Not connected`), so I’m proceeding with direct repository reads only and will mark claims `UNKNOWN` where the files do not support them.I’m focusing this iteration on residual within-surface wrong-concern/phase waste, because prior findings already established asset and D4-instrument issues while H2 concern-level slicing remains explicitly deferred.The repository confirms the current router does surface slicing and OpenCode language slicing, but the Webflow side still has no equivalent concern sub-slice; I’m checking scenario reports now to quantify whether that gap is measured or only theoretical.Current smart routing explicitly states that Webflow has no language sub-slice, which makes Webflow concern/phase gating the only remaining structural over-routing lever after cross-surface and asset fixes.The D4 ablation file is pre-remediation only and still uses the approximate on/off rubric, so it cannot prove post-remediation routine usefulness. I’m using router/live scenario rows for D3 evidence instead of treating D4 as measured.Router-final contains 17 scored text scenarios, not just the 3 live routing scenarios; several post-fix failures cluster in cross-stack or unsupported cases, which matters for whether H2 concern slicing is a high-value D3 lever or a benchmark-scope artifact.The current router-final D3 data shows deterministic Webflow SD-001 has only 1 wasted of 6 after slicing, while live SD-001 reports 8 wasted of 16 and broad observed reads. That splits the lever: concern slicing has little deterministic headroom for SD-001 but live behavior still wastes reads through broad globs.The playbook loader confirms expected assets are captured but separate from expected resources; that means concern-slicing claims must distinguish scored D3/D2 from b...\n  Line 15: - Read playbook scenarios `SD-001`, `LS-001`, `LS-002`, `CS-001`, `CS-006`, `CS-007` at their cited line ranges.\n\n  Line 21: 2. **The current route-time filter already implements the shipped large levers, so H2’s remaining structural target is narrower than the round-1 framing.** Router replay filters by detected surface, drops `assets/*`, keeps Motion overlay, and slices OpenCode language folders; Webflow explicitly has no language sub-slice. Sources: `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs:225-253`, `.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/smart_routing.md:450-459`.\n\n  Line 27: 5. **Live SD-001 waste is real execution behavior, not just deterministic router structure.** Post-remediation live SD-001 still reports D3 `0.5` with `16` routed and `8` wasted, and observed reads include broad `assets/webflow/**/*` and `references/webflow/**/*` globs. Since live parsing uses the model’s stated `resources` and `assets` as `observedResources`, while observed file reads are only corroborating evidence, the reported D3 is a stated-route metric and the broad-glob cost is an additional unscored live-cost artifact. Sources: `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.json:87-135`, `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:149-167`.\n\n  Line 29: 6. **The strongest live D3 lever is “no broad skill-tree exploration,” not phase-gating the deterministic map.** Pre-remediation live SD-001 used broad `references/webflow/**/*.md`, `assets/webflow/**/*.md`, `references/universal/*.md`, and asset globs with D3 `0.4`; post-remediation SD-001 still has broad webflow globs but improved to D3 `0.5`. That gain is partly real stated-route tightening, but observed exploration cost remains undercounted by D3. Sources: `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/skill-benchmark-report.json:87-146`, `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.json:87-135`.\n\n  Line 33: 8. **Routine-task D4 cannot be inferred from H2.** D4 is still unscored in current live-remediated output, and the old ablation is only `n=2` with `attribution:\"approximate\"`; the routine loss on LS-001 is pre-remediation (`onScore 0.82`, `offScore 0.95`) and cannot validate whether concern slicing helps routine work now. Sources: `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.md:12-23`, `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/d4-ablation.json:1-17`.\n\n  Line 35: 9. **LS-002 is a valid third routine D4-R candidate and should test output usefulness, not recall.** The LS-002 playbook asks for a concrete Python CLI change (`--json-output` flag) and expects Python refs plus shared refs while excluding other languages; it is structurally analogous to LS-001 but not TypeScript, making it a good third routine scenario for testing whether the routed slice helps produce a correct small implementation plan. Sources: `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/005-opencode-python.md:16-38`, `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/004-opencode-typescript.md:16-38`.\n\n  Line 37: ## Implications for D3/D4\n\n  Line 39: For **D3**, the next real lever is not a broad H2 phase gate. The build-ready lever is narrower: add an explicit **live routing discipline guard** that forbids broad `references/**` and `assets/**` globs after `sk-code` loads, requiring exact files from the stated route unless the agent declares an on-demand deep-dive reason. This targets real observed behavior in live runs and avoids D2 regression.\n\n  Line 45: For **D4**, H2’s usefulness gain is UNKNOWN. The existing D4 evidence is pre-remediation, approximate, and only two cases. The next useful D4 work should run a task-usefulness instrument on LS-001 plus LS-002: compare whether the slice leads to correct concrete steps, correct verification command, and no irrelevant cross-surface advice. Do not score it as resource recall.\n\n  Line 52: - Artifact: D4 improvement remains unproven until post-remediation ablation uses a task-usefulness grader and at least a third routine scenario.\n\n  Line 58: - A post-remediation D4-R routine instrument using LS-001 and LS-002, graded on output usefulness rather than recall.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/011-sk-code-routing-efficiency-remediation/research/iterations/iteration-006.md:\n  Line 1: I’ll ground this iteration in the benchmark and routing files first, then focus on one still-underexplored lever instead of revisiting shipped routing changes.The D4 lever is the least settled: the code labels it approximate, the report set is tiny, and existing scoring measures output quality deltas rather than whether the routed slice supports concrete routine actions. I’ll use that as the primary focus.The existing reports confirm D4 is not part of the live-remediated aggregate and the only saved D4 ablation is the pre-remediation two-scenario run. I’ll inspect the playbook scenario definitions to propose a measurable routine-task instrument and a concrete third scenario from authored coverage gaps.The playbook already has multiple routine OpenCode language scenarios with pass/fail criteria, but the saved D4 ablation used only LS-001. I’ll inspect the grader and live parsing to separate what D4 currently grades from what it should measure.The current grader is explicitly a hallucination/output-quality grader, not a task-execution usefulness probe. That means D4’s name and implementation are diverging for this follow-on question.## Focus\n\n  Line 2: I chose lever 3: D4 measurement. It is the highest-value unexplored lever because the repository’s current post-remediation reports still do not score D4, while the only saved D4 artifact is a two-scenario, pre-remediation, “approximate” ablation. That makes any claim about routine-task usefulness currently UNKNOWN, and it also makes it hard to tell whether D3 gains are real user-cost reductions or scoring artifacts.\n\n  Line 5: - Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/d4-ablation.cjs:5-15`, `:35-52`, `:58-80` to inspect the current D4 ablation design, formula, and contamination guard.\n\n  Line 7: - Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:35-52`, `:125-168` to inspect the live prompt and how stated resources, assets, and observed reads are parsed.\n\n  Line 8: - Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs:94-118`, `:130-131`, `:152-161`, `:254-275` to inspect D2/D3/D4 scoring and aggregation.\n\n  Line 11: - Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/router-final/skill-benchmark-report.json:18-40`, `:193-304`, `:330-496`, `:687-730`, `:912-989` to inspect current router-mode scenario-level D2/D3/D4.\n\n  Line 12: - Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/README.md:16-33`, `:73-101` to verify documented corpus, trace modes, and D4 artifact status.\n\n  Line 13: - Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:43-49`, `:109-125`, `:189-198`, `:272-287`, `:291-322` to ground the usefulness target in the authored playbook.\n\n  Line 14: - Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/004-opencode-typescript.md:14-39`, `005-opencode-python.md:14-39`, `006-opencode-shell.md:12-36`, and `007-opencode-config.md:12-36` to identify routine OPENCODE scenarios beyond LS-001.\n\n  Line 15: - Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/01--surface-detection/002-opencode-detection.md:16-49`, `:80-91` to inspect a routine implementation-style outcome contract.\n\n  Line 16: - Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/browser-executor.cjs:4-16`, `:62-82`, `:88-113` to compare D4 with an executor that measures actual behavior.\n\n  Line 19: 1. **f-i6-01: Post-remediation D4 is still unmeasured, so the routine-usefulness lift is UNKNOWN.** The live-remediated report has aggregate `79` but `D4.score: null` and `status: \"unscored-mode-a\"` (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.json:11-39`). The scorer hardcodes aggregate D4 as null/unscored for all reports (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs:254-264`). The only saved D4 artifact is the live-final ablation with `D4_aggregate: 49`, `scoredCount: 2`, `total: 2`, and `attribution: \"approximate\"` (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/d4-ablation.json:1-7`).\n\n  Line 21: 2. **f-i6-02: The current D4 ablation is not a direct usefulness instrument; it reuses a hallucination grader.** `d4-ablation.cjs` calls `grader.gradeD4` on skill-on and skill-off text, then computes `0.5 + (onScore - offScore) / 2` (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/d4-ablation.cjs:47-52`). The grader system prompt says its job is “D4 Hallucination” and tells it not to score correctness, paths, or planning structure (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/grader/prompts/system-grader.md:3-4`, `:22-41`). Therefore LS-001’s stored `score: 0.435` means “skill-on had lower hallucination-grade output than skill-off,” not “the skill made the routine task less useful” (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/d4-ablation.json:10-17`).\n\n  Line 23: 3. **f-i6-03: The live benchmark prompt prevents measuring what the model does with the slice.** The live executor reframes scenarios as “routing only,” says “do NOT edit files,” and asks for a fenced JSON block listing surface/resources/assets/agent (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:35-52`). The playbook’s acceptance model, however, requires the AI’s user-visible outcome to be sound (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:43-49`, `:109-119`). Example: SD-002’s desired outcome is an actual TypeScript-aware fix plus verification evidence, while its routing test metadata says not to actually edit during routing tests (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/01--surface-detection/002-opencode-detection.md:46-49`, `:102-107`). Current D4 cannot see that outcome gap.\n\n  Line 25: 4. **f-i6-04: Current live D3 is also partly a measurement artifact because it scores stated routing, not actual observed exploration cost.** `parseLiveResult` sets `observedResources` to the union of stated JSON `resources` and stated JSON `assets`, while `observedReads` are stored only under `raw` (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:149-168`). `scoreScenario` then computes D3 from `routerResult.resources`, `routedCount`, and expected-resource waste (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs:102-118`). In live-remediated CS-001, the row scores D3 at `0.6667` from `routedCount: 15`, `wastedCount: 5`, but raw observed reads include broad `references/**/*.md`, `assets/**/*.md`, and `assets/motion_dev/snippets/*` globs (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.json:320-368`). That means the current D3 gain is real for stated first-slice routing, but not yet proven real for actual model exploration cost.\n\n  Line 27: 5. **f-i6-05: The repository already has enough routine-task scenarios to fix D4’s n=2 problem without inventing a new corpus.** The playbook defines four OPENCODE language-sub-detection scenarios LS-001 through LS-004 (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:189-198`) and lists 24 total scenarios across seven categories (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:291-322`). LS-002 is a clean third routine candidate: “add a `--json-output` flag” to `skill_advisor.py`, expected `OPENCODE` + `PYTHON`, expected python/shared refs, expected python/universal assets, and no TypeScript/Shell/Config refs (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/005-opencode-python.md:14-39`). LS-003 and LS-004 provide shell/config follow-ups (`006-opencode-shell.md:12-36`, `007-opencode-config.md:12-36`).\n\n  Line 29: 6. **f-i6-06: A build-ready D4-R instrument should be action-scored, not recall-scored.** The current playbook already defines the needed acceptance axes: exact prompt, advisor/surface/resource evidence, loaded refs/assets, agent dispatch, and user-visible outcome (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:75-84`, `:109-125`). The D4-R harness should run skill-on/skill-off in a no-write “produce a minimal patch plan or unified diff plus verification commands” mode, then score: task-action correctness, surface/language contamination, verification fit, and hallucinated symbol/path risk. This would measure whether the slice helps the model produce a better routine answer, while D2/D3 continue measuring routing recall/efficiency.\n\n  Line 31: 7. **f-i6-07: The third routine scenario should be LS-002 first, not a synthetic new file.** LS-002 differs from LS-001 by language, target file, and expected reference family while staying routine and non-browser (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/005-opencode-python.md:16-39`). With current n=2, each scenario contributes 50 percentage points to the D4 mean; adding LS-002 drops that to 33.3 points per scenario. If the three scores were LS-001 `0.435`, CS-001 `0.55`, and a neutral LS-002 `0.50`, D4 would be `49.5`, effectively unchanged from the stored `49`; if LS-002 matched LS-001, D4 would fall to `47.3`. That shows the currently reported D4 magnitude is too sample-sensitive to guide remediation.\n\n  Line 33: ## Implications for D3/D4\n\n  Line 34: - **D4 real-vs-artifact:** The stored `49` is mostly a measurement artifact for this question. It is sourced from a hallucination grader and two scenarios, not from a post-remediation routine-task usefulness run. The real post-remediation D4 is UNKNOWN until an action-scored D4-R suite is run.\n\n  Line 36: - **Expected D4 magnitude:** Adding LS-002 as a third routine probe will not by itself “lift” D4; it will make the estimate less volatile. The likely immediate gain is measurement honesty, not a score bump.\n\n  Line 37: - **Concrete next build lever:** Add D4-R as a separate reported dimension or D4 subscore: `D4_hallucination_delta` for the existing grader and `D4_task_outcome_delta` for routine usefulness. Do not collapse them into one number until both are populated.\n\n  Line 38: - **Routine suite proposal:** Run LS-001, LS-002, LS-003, LS-004, plus SD-002 in no-write patch-plan mode. Use CS-001 separately as a domain-pattern usefulness probe, not as evidence for routine OPENCODE usefulness.\n\n  Line 39: - **Pass condition for a real D4 lift:** Skill-on must improve task-action correctness or verification fit versus skill-off, without simply naming more expected resources and without increasing observed broad globs. If the only improvement is better path naming or fewer hallucinated symbols, classify it as benchmark-fidelity improvement, not routine usefulness.\n\n  Line 42: - Concern-level / phase-gated slicing is still the main unexplored routing lever after D4 measurement. It should inspect residual within-surface waste after language sub-slicing, especially Webflow implementation-vs-verification-vs-performance overlap.\n\n  Line 43: - The assets-scoring seam still needs an explicit scored-gold experiment, but prior findings already established the parser/scorer mismatch.\n\n  Line 45: - No repository evidence currently proves post-remediation D4 routine usefulness. UNKNOWN until the D4-R harness runs.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/011-sk-code-routing-efficiency-remediation/research/iterations/iteration-005.md:\n  Line 3: I chose **gold↔map reconciliation**, expanded to include prompt-source drift, because iteration #4 already showed the assets seam changes D2 honesty but not current deterministic D3. The remaining high-value question is whether SD-001 and CS-001 are low because `RESOURCE_MAP` is genuinely missing behavior-critical coverage, or because the benchmark gold/prompt/scorer is measuring the wrong thing.\n\n  Line 14: - Read live and D4 measurement harnesses: `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:15-19`, `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:149-168`, `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/d4-ablation.cjs:4-16`, `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/d4-ablation.cjs:35-52`, `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/d4-ablation.json:1-28`.\n\n  Line 32: 8. Live-remediated scores are not a clean proof that the router solved CS-001. The live report scores CS-001 D2 `1`, D3 `0.6667`, routed `15`, wasted `5`